  footnotes: []
english:
  title: In Imitation of the Ancients
  author: Lee Hun
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Yesterday the tree stood clothed in blossoms,
    Today the flowers have left the branches.
    Why does the east wind hurry so?
    Ceaseless in its urge to open flowers.

    When flowers bloom, do not rejoice,
    When flowers fall, do not grieve.
    Though these blossoms now have scattered,
    There will come a time they bloom again.

    Do you not see in that bronze mirror,
    How the rosy cheeks fade day by day?
    Both the wise and foolish return to dust,
    Crumbled tombs stand scattered and forlorn.

    Let us put such thoughts aside and drink fine wine—
    What good is sorrow and lamentation in the end?
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: The 'bronze mirror' (청동, blue bronze) is a traditional metaphor for time's passage and the aging of beauty, suggesting reflection on mortality itself.
  - key: ''
    value: This poem employs the classical theme of *carpe diem* common to both Chinese and Korean poetry, balancing acceptance of life's transience with the gentle encouragement to find solace in simple pleasures.
